(466, 1, '2014-09-18 19:05:34', '2014-09-18 19:05:34', 'It turns out you actually can teach an old dog new tricks. Million-dollar tricks, in fact. Just ask the Olate Dogs'' human crew, who won America’s Got Talent in 2012 alongside 25 of their poodles. For a group that has performed for audiences at Radio City Music Hall, the Las Vegas strip and elsewhere around the world, the Olate Dogs'' beginnings are exceptionally humble.<span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2411"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/olate-dogs-2-300x1994jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Olate-Dogs-2-300x199_4.jpg?itok=xGEllKjF" alt="Olate Dogs 2" width="220" height="146" /></a></span>\r\n\r\n“My father, Richard Olate, was brought up in in extreme poverty in Chili as the second youngest of 22 children,” said Nicholas Olate, the 21 year old who serves as the right-hand man for his dad during their performances. “He often went days without food and would frequently knock on people’s doors asking for leftovers or donations. Around the age of 12, to make a little money, he found a stray dog, started training it and began doing street performances.”\r\nOlate Sr.’s entrepreneurial spirit led him to take in and train more homeless dogs and eventually pitch his act to circuses in South America. Slowly, he and his dogs began to gain attention, but their struggles were far from over.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n“Success with the circuses required my dad to sacrifice a lot,” said Olate Jr. “He often had to walk miles to make it to a show, sleep in tents or ask strangers to take him in.”\r\n\r\nEventually, though, an American talent scout noticed Olate’s act and offered him a spot in a California-based circus.\r\n\r\n“From there, the show went from nothing to big scale,” said Olate Jr. “And even though my dad did things like perform for Michael Jackson and star in TV commercials, he stayed humble and didn’t let it get to his head.”\r\n\r\nIn 2012, the Olate Dogs’ unique performances landed them a spot on America’s Got Talent, where they went on to win the million-dollar prize and the opportunity to star in a show in Las Vegas, the first non-singing act to do so.\r\n\r\n“Being on America’s Got Talent was such a learning experience for us because we were performing alongside a bunch of amazing acts,” said Olate Jr. “Winning has opened up so many doors and opportunities for us.”\r\n\r\nThe Olate Dogs now travel around the country performing, with their next show at Bridgeland’s Howl-O-Ween Fest on Saturday, Oct. 25 from 10 am – 4 pm. The sixth annual event raises funds for Houston-area rescue groups, a cause near to the Olate Dogs'' hearts.\r\n\r\n“My dad likes to tell me that he doesn’t know if he rescued the animals or if they rescued him,” said Olate Jr. “Who knows where he’d be if he hadn’t found those dogs.”\r\n\r\nTo learn more about Howl-O-Ween Fest, visit <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/howl-o-ween-fest.com">www.bridgeland.com/howl-o-ween-fest.com</a>. Bridgeland is a wholly-owned subsidiary of The Howard Hughes Corporation and part of The Woodlands Development Company.', 'Member of Olate Dogs Reflects on the Group''s Humble Start', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'member-of-olate-dogs-reflects-on-the-groups-humble-start', '', '', '2015-09-24 19:06:59', '2015-09-24 19:06:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=466', 0, 'post', '', 0),
