(473, 1, '2015-09-24 19:15:26', '2015-09-24 19:15:26', 'Two well-respected builders, David Weekley and J. Kyle, will soon begin selling homes in the newest sections of Lakeland Heights. Starting in the $250s, these homes will be set on 50’ and 60’ foot lots and range in square footage.<span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2376"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/bridgeland-8754wk3-300x1964jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/bridgeland-8754_wk3-300x196_4.jpg?itok=ESxqxEUO" alt="Lakeland Heights" width="220" height="144" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nAs Bridgeland’s traditional neighborhood design (TND) development, Lakeland Heights was created to have the aesthetic appeal and accessibility of classic Houston neighborhoods like The Heights and West University, but with the updated amenities of a new community. Consequently, homes in Lakeland Heights blend Craftsmen, English Tudor, Classical and French styles and are walking distance from parks, recreational facilities and schools. Eventually, residents will also be able to easily access shops and restaurants in Lakeland Village Center, a commercial anchor for the 350-home community.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nFestival Park, a hub of the community, contains a covered pavilion for outdoor concerts, plays and performances. The pavilion also houses picnic tables, restrooms and a fireplace with a seating area. Another highlight is Lakeland Heights'' half-mile waterway, which features a landmark bridge, trails, creatively landscaped park space and seating areas\r\n\r\nFor more information on Lakeland Heights, visit <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/lakeland-heights">http://www.bridgeland.com/lakeland-heights</a>.', 'David Weekley and J. Kyle Begin Selling Homes in Newest Sections of Lakeland Heights', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '472-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 19:15:26', '2015-09-24 19:15:26', '', 472, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/472-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(474, 1, '2014-07-30 19:15:34', '2014-07-30 19:15:34', 'Alongside a demonstration on how to make homemade pickles, artisan merchants, local farmers and other unique vendors will set up shop at The Farmers Market at <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">Bridgeland</a> Sunday, Aug. 10 from 12:30-3:30 p.m.<span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2371"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/bridgeland-august-farmers-market-198x3009jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Bridgeland-August-Farmers-Market-198x300_9.jpg?itok=J1MV9j3E" alt="Bridgeland Farmers Market" width="145" height="220" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nPEAS Farm, a vendor based out of Conroe that typically supplies seasonal produce, free-range eggs and local honey at the market, will lead the pickling demonstration and also sell pickling kits, complete with cucumbers, seasoning, vinegar and a jar.\r\n\r\nA variety of local produce will also be available to shoppers, including peak-season melons, tomatillos, eggplants, green peppers, okra and squash.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nRun by a team of Bridgeland volunteers that are dedicated to bringing fresh, homegrown food to Cypress residents, the market’s mission is to support and promote our area’s food system, while also providing educational events that enlighten consumers on the value of shopping locally.\r\n\r\nAlthough The Farmers Market at Bridgeland was originally created to be a one-time sale, the event was so well received by the community that it has evolved into a recurring happening, now taking place on the second Sunday of every month. The gatherings continue to attract more vendors and attendees, with last month’s market reaching record attendance levels.\r\n\r\nThe Farmers Market at Bridgeland is held at Lakeland Activity Center, 16902 Bridgeland Landing. To see a full list of participating vendors, visit <a href="http://www.farmersmarketatbridgeland.org/">www.farmersmarketatbridgeland.org</a>.', 'The Farmers Market at Bridgeland to Feature Pickling Demonstration and Fresh Produce Aug. 10', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-farmers-market-at-bridgeland-to-feature-pickling-demonstration-and-fresh-produce-aug-10', '', '', '2015-09-24 19:16:06', '2015-09-24 19:16:06', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=474', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(475, 1, '2015-09-24 19:16:06', '2015-09-24 19:16:06', 'Alongside a demonstration on how to make homemade pickles, artisan merchants, local farmers and other unique vendors will set up shop at The Farmers Market at <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">Bridgeland</a> Sunday, Aug. 10 from 12:30-3:30 p.m.<span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2371"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/bridgeland-august-farmers-market-198x3009jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Bridgeland-August-Farmers-Market-198x300_9.jpg?itok=J1MV9j3E" alt="Bridgeland Farmers Market" width="145" height="220" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nPEAS Farm, a vendor based out of Conroe that typically supplies seasonal produce, free-range eggs and local honey at the market, will lead the pickling demonstration and also sell pickling kits, complete with cucumbers, seasoning, vinegar and a jar.\r\n\r\nA variety of local produce will also be available to shoppers, including peak-season melons, tomatillos, eggplants, green peppers, okra and squash.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nRun by a team of Bridgeland volunteers that are dedicated to bringing fresh, homegrown food to Cypress residents, the market’s mission is to support and promote our area’s food system, while also providing educational events that enlighten consumers on the value of shopping locally.\r\n\r\nAlthough The Farmers Market at Bridgeland was originally created to be a one-time sale, the event was so well received by the community that it has evolved into a recurring happening, now taking place on the second Sunday of every month. The gatherings continue to attract more vendors and attendees, with last month’s market reaching record attendance levels.\r\n\r\nThe Farmers Market at Bridgeland is held at Lakeland Activity Center, 16902 Bridgeland Landing. To see a full list of participating vendors, visit <a href="http://www.farmersmarketatbridgeland.org/">www.farmersmarketatbridgeland.org</a>.', 'The Farmers Market at Bridgeland to Feature Pickling Demonstration and Fresh Produce Aug. 10', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '474-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 19:16:06', '2015-09-24 19:16:06', '', 474, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/474-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(476, 1, '2014-07-02 19:16:25', '2014-07-02 19:16:25', 'Developers at Bridgeland strive to not only preserve, restore and enhance the 11,400-acre community’s natural surroundings, but Houston’s as well.  Consequently, Bridgeland is a proud sponsor of the <i>Great Green Quest</i>, a city-wide effort to teach students about Houston’s ten unique eco-regions.\r\n\r\nEco-regions are large areas of land or water that contain geographically-distinct assemblies of species, natural communities and environmental conditions. The <i>Great Green Quest</i>, which was founded by Houston Wilderness, encourages students to study and explore these local eco-regions, which are distributed throughout the city. <span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2366"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/butterfly-catching-200x3004jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Butterfly-Catching-200x300_4.jpg?itok=d0LphBDJ" alt="Butterfly Catching" width="147" height="220" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nBefore the start of the summer, Houston Wilderness team members distribute eco-region passports to elementary-aged students across the city. Recipients are challenged to explore six of Houston’s ten eco-regions over their summer break.\r\n\r\n“Many people – especially young students – don’t realize that Houston isn’t just a city of flat nothingness,” said Debra January-Beavers, president and CEO of Houston Wilderness. “The program encourages children to protect, preserve and promote nature while teaching them about our area’s natural treasures.”\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nGreat Green Quest began in 2013 with six inner-city schools, but has since expanded to 10 schools that are located throughout the Houston area, including elementaries in Spring Branch and Lamar school districts.\r\n\r\n“The program really resonates with children and families,” said January-Beavers. “It gives them an opportunity to discover their city and do something different over their vacation.”\r\n\r\nFor the last 11 years, Houston Wilderness has been dedicated to bringing together a broad-based alliance of individuals, businesses, environmental and government interests to guard the greater Houston region’s ecological treasures. For more information on the organization or the Great Green quest, visit <a href="http://houstonwilderness.org/">http://houstonwilderness.org/</a>.', 'Bridgeland Sponsors Houston Wilderness'' Great Green Quest', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bridgeland-sponsors-houston-wilderness-great-green-quest', '', '', '2015-09-24 19:16:55', '2015-09-24 19:16:55', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=476', 0, 'post', '', 0),
