(492, 1, '2014-04-26 20:00:35', '2014-04-26 20:00:35', 'Event-goers at<b> </b><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">Bridgeland’s</a> Nature Fest made history today by setting a new Guinness World Records® title for the most people giving a simultaneous bird call.<span class="caption none media-image alignright size-full wp-image-2314"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/535f14521b6eepreview-300jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/535f14521b6ee.preview-300.jpg?itok=RYp21Gar" alt="bird watcher Gary Clark" width="220" height="146" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nThe official tally was 994 people, an increase of 24 percent from the previous record of 801 people making a bird call, which was set in September 2011 during the Midwest Birding Symposium.\r\n\r\nHouston Chronicle nature columnist and noted bird watcher Gary Clark led the attempt in Bridgeland, teaching the Nature Fest crowd how to call the northern cardinal, common to the Houston area and known for the male’s bright red plumage. To break the world record, the call had to be held for 10 seconds or more. An official GUINNESS WORLD Records® Adjudicator, Sarah Wilcox, was on site to verify the attempt.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n“This record stood for two and a half years, so for it to be beaten by this much is really fantastic,” Wilcox said. “It is always impressive to see numbers of people come together to set large records like this, especially those that require instruction and experts.”\r\n\r\nAccording to Guinness World Records, more than 50,000 record applications are received each year, with about 55 percent accepted by the organization. Worldwide, about 8 percent of those whose applications are accepted set a new world record each year. In the United States, the number drops to a 5 percent successful completion rate annually.\r\n\r\n“We are thrilled we could set a new GUINNESS WORLD Records® title,” said Lona Shipp, marketing manager for Bridgeland, a master planned community in Cypress. “This required careful planning and many volunteers to ensure the number of participants were making legitimate bird calls.”\r\n\r\nThis was Bridgeland’s seventh year to hold Nature Fest, a day of nature-themed entertainment and activities, including stage shows, roaming performers, camel and pony rides, kayaking lessons and bumper boating. In addition to the world record attempt, other event highlights included Staples Animal Safari and the Circus Safari performance.\r\n\r\nBridgeland is a wholly-owned subsidiary of <a href="http://www.howardhughes.com/">The Howard Hughes Corporation</a> and part of <a href="http://www.thewoodlands.com/">The Woodlands Development Company</a>.', 'Bridgeland Sets New GUINNESS WORLD RECORDS® Title at Nature Fest', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bridgeland-sets-new-guinness-world-records-title-at-nature-fest', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:02:05', '2015-09-24 20:02:05', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=492', 0, 'post', '', 0),
