(513, 1, '2014-01-16 20:12:35', '2014-01-16 20:12:35', 'According to a recent <a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2014/01/16/houston-jumps-to-no-2-on-ulis.html?ana=twt">Houston Business Journal article</a>, the Urban Land Institute ranked Houston the No. 2 market to watch in its <a href="http://www.uli.org/wp-content/uploads/ULI-Documents/Emerging-Trends-in-Real-Estate-Americas-2014.pdf">“Emerging Trends in Real Estate 2014” report</a>. . <span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2225"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600-600-300x2004jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600-600-300x200_4.jpg?itok=BOtuN4Na" alt="houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600 600" width="220" height="147" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nULI’s reasoning is not that surprising: “Houston’s booming energy economy has fueled an active real estate market over the past few  years, and survey respondents expect that to continue in the coming year.”\r\n\r\nWhile Houston came in behind San Francisco on the overall list, it took the top spot for investment real estate. Houston is the No. 2 market for home-building prospects and No. 3 for development.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nIn the investment arena, survey respondents overwhelming ranked Houston a “buy” in all five property types: office, industrial, retail, apartments and hotel. Not surprisingly, the city saw its highest ranking in the apartment sector, ranking No. 1 on that list. Houston has seen a plans, the past few weeks, especially in the luxury arena.\r\n\r\nThe city''s highest score was in the industrial sector, but Miami beat it out for the No. 1 spot.\r\n\r\nAs Houston continues to expand in 2014, ULI expects housing, nonresidential construction and a revival in exploration industries to be the key economic drivers.\r\n\r\n“Employment gains are projected to come from related manufacturing and professional services, as large companies relocate more of their headquarters operations to Houston,” ULI wrote. “Over the longer term, above-average population growth and expansion in energy, health-related and distribution industries will help propel above-average economic growth.”\r\n\r\nOther Texas markets moved around the list, as well, with Dallas-Fort Worth jumping four spots to No. 5, and Austin slipping three spots to No. 7. San Antonio moved up from No. 19 to No. 14.\r\n\r\nA recent Forbes article also listed Houston as a city with large development potential, stating that it has an “undervalued” housing market.  Read more about that <a href="http://realtormag.realtor.org/daily-news/2013/12/30/housings-best-buys-for-2014">here</a>.', 'Houston - Hot Real Estate Market for 2014', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'houston-hot-real-estate-market-for-2014', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:13:04', '2015-09-24 20:13:04', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=513', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(514, 1, '2015-09-24 20:13:04', '2015-09-24 20:13:04', 'According to a recent <a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2014/01/16/houston-jumps-to-no-2-on-ulis.html?ana=twt">Houston Business Journal article</a>, the Urban Land Institute ranked Houston the No. 2 market to watch in its <a href="http://www.uli.org/wp-content/uploads/ULI-Documents/Emerging-Trends-in-Real-Estate-Americas-2014.pdf">“Emerging Trends in Real Estate 2014” report</a>. . <span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2225"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600-600-300x2004jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600-600-300x200_4.jpg?itok=BOtuN4Na" alt="houstonskyline-downtown-night-thinkstock600 600" width="220" height="147" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nULI’s reasoning is not that surprising: “Houston’s booming energy economy has fueled an active real estate market over the past few  years, and survey respondents expect that to continue in the coming year.”\r\n\r\nWhile Houston came in behind San Francisco on the overall list, it took the top spot for investment real estate. Houston is the No. 2 market for home-building prospects and No. 3 for development.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nIn the investment arena, survey respondents overwhelming ranked Houston a “buy” in all five property types: office, industrial, retail, apartments and hotel. Not surprisingly, the city saw its highest ranking in the apartment sector, ranking No. 1 on that list. Houston has seen a plans, the past few weeks, especially in the luxury arena.\r\n\r\nThe city''s highest score was in the industrial sector, but Miami beat it out for the No. 1 spot.\r\n\r\nAs Houston continues to expand in 2014, ULI expects housing, nonresidential construction and a revival in exploration industries to be the key economic drivers.\r\n\r\n“Employment gains are projected to come from related manufacturing and professional services, as large companies relocate more of their headquarters operations to Houston,” ULI wrote. “Over the longer term, above-average population growth and expansion in energy, health-related and distribution industries will help propel above-average economic growth.”\r\n\r\nOther Texas markets moved around the list, as well, with Dallas-Fort Worth jumping four spots to No. 5, and Austin slipping three spots to No. 7. San Antonio moved up from No. 19 to No. 14.\r\n\r\nA recent Forbes article also listed Houston as a city with large development potential, stating that it has an “undervalued” housing market.  Read more about that <a href="http://realtormag.realtor.org/daily-news/2013/12/30/housings-best-buys-for-2014">here</a>.', 'Houston - Hot Real Estate Market for 2014', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '513-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:13:04', '2015-09-24 20:13:04', '', 513, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/513-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(515, 1, '2014-01-10 20:13:10', '2014-01-10 20:13:10', 'Expecting resolution-discerning attendees on the hunt for healthful items, vendors at The Farmers Market at <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">Bridgeland</a>will be selling a plethora of peak-season vegetables, ripe produce, grass-fed meats and free-range eggs, 12:30 – 3:30 p.m. Sunday, January 12.\r\n\r\nWhile <a href="http://cloud9pies.net/home.html">Cloud 9 Pies</a> offers products that most calorie-cognizant buyers might typically steer clear of, Susan Crowson, owner  of the local baked-goods shop, hopes her unique twist on homemade sweets will keep the market’s crowd interested.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n“I bake my pies in four-ounce mason jars, so it’s just an individual serving,” Crowson said. “Everything is fresh and made  with local, simple ingredients you can actually pronounce.”\r\n\r\nIn addition to being pint-sized, Crowson’s pies also are available in gluten-free and sugar-free varieties. Shoppers craving a  more classic flavor and size, however, can enjoy her pecan, apple and fudge pies in either a four-ounce serving or a standard  deep-dish pie pan.\r\n\r\nOpen to the public, The Farmers Market at Bridgeland is held on the second Sunday of each month near Bridgeland’s  Lakeland Activity Center, 16902 Bridgeland Landing. To see a full list of this month’s participating vendors, visit www.farmersmarketatbridgeland.org.  Learn more about Bridgeland, a wholly owned subsidiary of <a href="http://www.howardhughes.com/">The Howard Hughes  Corporation</a> and part of <a href="http://www.thewoodlands.com/">The Woodlands Development Company</a>, at <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">www.bridgeland.com</a>.', 'First Farmers Market of 2014 Features Produce, Pint-Sized Pies', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'first-farmers-market-of-2014-features-produce-pint-sized-pies', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:13:31', '2015-09-24 20:13:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/Bridgeland/?p=515', 0, 'post', '', 0),
